While the data is not crystal clear, the above generally corroborates the idea that financial bubbles have formed during times of increased leverage. Let's calculate each group's standard distance from their median line:

::: panel-tabset
#### Metric 1


::: {.cell .column-page}

```{.r .cell-code}
r3000_nested %>% 
    select(date:bucket, -year, balance_sheet, classification) %>% 
    unnest(c(balance_sheet, classification)) %>% 
    mutate(d_e = (st_debt + lt_debt) / total_equity) %>% 
    select(date:bucket, classification_1, d_e) %>% 
    group_by(date, classification_1, bucket) %>% 
    summarize(d_e = median(d_e, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    group_by(classification_1, bucket) %>% 
    mutate(med_d_e = median(d_e, na.rm = T)) %>% 
    mutate(distance = d_e - med_d_e) %>% 
    mutate(avg_distance = mean(abs(distance), na.rm = T)) %>% 
    mutate(standardized_distance = distance / avg_distance) %>% 
    ungroup() %>% 
    ggplot(aes(date, standardized_distance, color = bucket)) +
    geom_line() +
    theme_tq(base_size = 16) +
