### 3) New Entrants to the Market

There are several ways we can assess whether new players are entering markets. The most direct and simple way is to track when private companies become public (i.e. IPO data). This method is likely to produce the clearest results, but it has a glaring shortfall - the classification scheme of our IPO data is different.

::: panel-tabset
#### Aggregate


::: {.cell .column-page}

```{.r .cell-code}
ipo_data %>%
    filter(country == "UNITED STATES") %>%
    filter(!(industry_sector %in% c("N.A.", "Government"))) %>%
    mutate(floor_date = floor_date(announced_date, unit = "month")) %>% 
    count(announced_date) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(announced_date, n)) +
    geom_col(color = palette_light()[1]) +
    theme_tq(base_size = 16) +
    labs(
        x="", y="", title = "# of IPOs (Monthly)"
    )
```

