A third, albeit indirect method of assessing market entrants is to track the proportion of the labor force in different markets and its growth rate. It is likely that the labor force will shift towards segments of the market where bubbles are forming because workers tend to be well compensated during these times.


::: {.cell .column-page}

```{.r .cell-code}
labor_force <- read_rds(here("raw_data", "Financial Bubbles", "labor_force.rds"))

r3000_nested %>%
    select(date, misc, classification) %>%
    unnest(c(misc, classification)) %>%
    select(date, num_employees, classification_1) %>%
    group_by(date, classification_1) %>%
    summarize(tot_employees = sum(num_employees, na.rm = T)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    left_join(labor_force) %>%
    mutate(prop = tot_employees / labor_force) %>%
    ggplot(aes(date, prop)) +
    geom_line() +
    theme_tq(base_size = 16) +
    theme(title = element_text(hjust = .5)) +
    scale_color_tq() +
    facet_wrap(~classification_1, scales = "free", ncol = 3) +
    labs(x="", y = "", color = "", title = "Proportion of Labor Force") +
    scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::label_percent()) +
    scale_x_date(labels = scales::label_date(format = "'%y"), date_breaks = "5 years")
